the 9th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Tenmu|qq=}} ({{ill|680|ja|680|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/680|qq=}}) with {{ill|Toneri-ō|ja|舎人王|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toneri-ō|qq=}},<ref>'Nihon Shoki': Emperor Tenmu, 9th year, July 25 entry</ref> and in January of the 1st year of {{ill|Empress Jitō|ja|持統天皇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Jitō|qq=}} ({{ill|687|ja|687|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/687|qq=}}) with {{ill|Abe Goshujin|ja|阿倍御主人|lt=Fuse Goshujin|lt_ja=布勢御主人|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe Goshujin|qq=}}.<ref>'Nihon Shoki': Empress Jitō, January 1 entry</ref> Since no ministers were appointed during the Tenmu period, the position of Nagon was the highest administrative office. The title “Nagon” is of Chinese origin, as seen in the "Shuntian" of the {{ill|Shu Jing|ja|書経|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shu Jing|qq=}}, and in the early Sui and Tang dynasties it was the title for the head ({{ill|Chamberlain|ja|侍中|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chamberlain|qq=}}) of the {{ill|Monkashō|ja|門下省|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monkashō|qq=}}.
== Genealogy == * Father: {{ill|Kose Tokuda|ja|巨勢徳多|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kose Tokuda|qq=}} * Mother: Unknown * Children by an unknown consort: ** Son: {{ill|Kose Oharu|ja|巨勢邑治|lt=Oharu|lt_ja=邑治|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kose Oharu|qq=}} ** Son: {{ill|Kose Kooharu|ja|巨勢小邑治|lt=Kooharu|lt_ja=小邑治|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kose Kooharu|qq=}}
